card.desc: I have the router forwarding web (port 80) traffic to `tangela`, my nginx reverse proxy that is then able to parse the sub-domain and forward the traffic to the correct server. So for example, requests to `gitlab.himmelwright.net` get forwarded to `geodude`, my gitlab server VM. I need a way to do the same thing, but with port `22` for ssh (and eventually probably port `443` for https).

data.text: Going to start this on my gitlab probably and move it to Jenkins when it's further along.

So I think looking at the json output, I might be able to write a simple parser with python or something that can parse the json file, dumping it into a data structure, and then use that to export some *formatted* output for weekly notes that I can save each week, like I used to do with org mode.

The nice thing is that I can just make sure to download the json files for now and archive them, and then when I get the code setup I can rip through the files. If I want to update them as I made the output nicer, I should be able to just regenerate as long as I'm saving the old raws...

While this might take some work on my end... I think it might be doable. The hardest part will be figuring out how to take the parsed data and actually make it look like a nice looking output lol/
